===Etymology===
{{defdate|1437}} Borrowed from {{bor|en|frm|funerailles||funeral rites|g=p}}, from {{der|en|ML.|fūnerālia||funeral rites}}, originally neuter plural of {{der|en|LL.|fūnerālis||having to do with a funeral}}, from {{der|en|la|fūnus||funeral, death, corpse}}, origin unknown, perhaps ultimately from {{der|en|ine-pro|*dʰew-||to die}}. Singular and plural used interchangeably in English until circa 1700. The adjective {{m|en|funereal}} is first attested 1725, by influence of {{etyl|frm|en}} {{m|frm|funerail}}, from {{etyl|la|en}} {{m|la|funereus}}, from {{m|la|funus}}.

